# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drag-and-drop-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] It’s been available across browsers since September 2020.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] The **`DragEvent`** interface is a DOM event that represents a drag and drop interaction.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] The user initiates a drag by placing a pointer device (such as a mouse) on the touch surface and then dragging the pointer to a new location (such as another DOM element).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] Applications are free to interpret a drag and drop interaction in an application-specific way.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This interface inherits properties from `MouseEvent` and `Event`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] The data that is transferred during a drag and drop interaction.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] Although this interface has a constructor, it is not possible to create a useful DataTransfer object from script, since `DataTransfer` objects have a processing and security model that is coordinated by the browser during drag-and-drops.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] Creates a synthetic and untrusted DragEvent.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This event is fired when an element or text selection is being dragged.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This event is fired when a drag operation is being ended (by releasing a mouse button or hitting the escape key).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This event is fired when a dragged element or text selection enters a valid drop target.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This event is fired when a dragged element or text selection leaves a valid drop target.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This event is fired continuously when an element or text selection is being dragged and the mouse pointer is over a valid drop target (every 50 ms WHEN mouse is not moving ELSE much faster between 5 ms (slow movement) and 1ms (fast movement) approximately.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This firing pattern is different than `mouseover` ).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This event is fired when the user starts dragging an element or text selection.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] This event is fired when an element or text selection is dropped on a valid drop target.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/api-dragevent] An Example of each property, constructor, event type and global event handlers is included in their respective reference page.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] The **`DataTransfer`** object is used to hold any data transferred between contexts, such as a drag and drop operation, or clipboard read/write.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] It may hold one or more data items, each of one or more data types.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] `DataTransfer` was primarily designed for the HTML Drag and Drop API, as the `DragEvent.dataTransfer` property, and is still specified in the HTML drag-and-drop section, but it is now also used by other APIs, such as `ClipboardEvent.clipboardData` and `InputEvent.dataTransfer`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] However, other APIs only use certain parts of its interface, ignoring properties such as `dropEffect`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Documentation of `DataTransfer` will primarily discuss its usage in drag-and-drop operations, and you should refer to the other APIs' documentation for usage of `DataTransfer` in those contexts.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Creates and returns a new `DataTransfer` object.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Gets the type of drag-and-drop operation currently selected or sets the operation to a new type.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] The value must be `none`, `copy`, `link` or `move`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Provides all of the types of operations that are possible.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Must be one of `none`, `copy`, `copyLink`, `copyMove`, `link`, `linkMove`, `move`, `all` or `uninitialized`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Contains a list of all the local files available on the data transfer.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] If the drag operation doesn't involve dragging files, this property is an empty list.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Gives a `DataTransferItemList` object which is a list of all of the drag data.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] An array of strings giving the formats that were set in the `dragstart` event.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Sets the drag source for the given element.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] This will be the element on which `drag` and `dragend` events are fired, and not the default target (the node that was dragged).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Remove the data associated with a given type.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] If the type is empty or not specified, the data associated with all types is removed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] If data for the specified type does not exist, or the data transfer contains no data, this method will have no effect.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Retrieves the data for a given type, or an empty string if data for that type does not exist or the data transfer contains no data.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] If data for the type does not exist, it is added at the end, such that the last item in the types list will be the new format.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] If data for the type already exists, the existing data is replaced in the same position.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Set the image to be used for dragging if a custom one is desired.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] Every method and property listed in this document has its own reference page and each reference page either directly includes an example of the interface or has a link to an example.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] In the following example, we have a `<form>` containing three different types of text inputs: a text `<input>` element, a `<textarea>` element, and a `<div>` element with `contenteditable` set to `true`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/datatransfer] The user can paste or drop text into any of these elements, and the data in the `ClipboardEvent.clipboardData` or `DragEvent.dataTransfer` object will be displayed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] In computer graphical user interfaces, **drag and drop** is a pointing device gesture in which the user selects a virtual object by "grabbing" it and dragging it to a different location or onto another virtual object.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] In general, it can be used to invoke many kinds of actions, or create various types of associations between two abstract objects.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] As a feature, drag-and-drop support is not found in all software, though it is sometimes a fast and easy-to-learn technique.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] However, it is not always clear to users that an item can be dragged and dropped, or what command is performed by the drag and drop, which can decrease usability.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Dragging requires more physical effort than moving the same pointing device without holding down any buttons.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Because of this, a user cannot move as quickly and precisely while dragging (see Fitts' law).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] However, drag-and-drop operations have the advantage of thoughtfully chunking together two operands (the object to drag, and the drop location) into a single action.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Extended dragging and dropping (as in graphic design) can stress the mousing hand.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] A design problem appears when the same button selects and drags items.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Imprecise movement can cause an attempt to select an object to register as a dragging motion.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Another problem is that the target of the dropping can be hidden under other objects.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] The user would have to stop the dragging, make both the source and the target visible and start again.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] In classic Mac OS the top-of-screen menu bar served as a universal "drag cancel" target.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] This issue has been dealt with in Mac OS X with the introduction of Exposé.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Drag and drop, called **click and drag** at the time, was used in the original Macintosh to manipulate files (for example, copying them between disks or folders).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] System 7 added the ability to open a document in an application by dropping the document icon onto the application's icon.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Apple added "Macintosh Drag and Drop" to System 7.5, extending "click and drag" to common clipboard operations like copying or moving textual content within a document.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Content could also be dragged into the filesystem to create a "clipping file" which could then be stored and reused.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Files could also be dropped on application windows, for example to enclose a document in an email, or add an image to a word processor document.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] For most of its history, Mac OS has used a single button mouse with the button covering a large portion of the top surface of the mouse.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] This may mitigate the ergonomic concerns of keeping the button pressed while dragging.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] The Workplace Shell of OS/2 uses dragging and dropping extensively with the secondary mouse button, leaving the primary one for selection and clicking.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Its use like that of other advanced Common User Access features distinguished native OS/2 applications from platform-independent ports.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] The HTML5 working draft specification includes support for drag and drop.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Based on needed action, one of the above types can be used.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Note that when an HTML element is dragged for moving its current position, its ID is sent to the destination parent element; so it sends a text and can be considered as the first group.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Google's web-based e-mail application Gmail supports drag-and-drop of images and attachments in the latest Google Chrome browser and Apple's Safari (5.x).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Google Images permits users to drag and drop image files into a browser to perform a reverse image search.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] A drag and drop website builder (also called DIY website builders) offers a visual interface where users can create and customize their websites by simply "dragging" and "dropping" various elements onto a page without the need for development experience or knowledge of coding languages.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] No-code platforms have progressed well beyond the capabilities of early visual editors.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] With the advent of Artificial intelligence (AI), building a website has become even quicker.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] As of May 2025, more than 21 million websites were constructed with usage of drag and drop website builder.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Wix accounted for roughly one-third of websites built with drag-and-drop website builders.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Others, such as Weebly, Hostinger, and GoDaddy, are also active in the market.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Touch screen interfaces also include drag and drop, or more precisely, long press, and then drag, e.g. on the iPhone or Android home screens.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] iOS 11 implements a drag-and-drop feature which allows the user to touch items (and tap with other fingers to drag more) within an app or between apps on iPads.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] On iPhones, the functionality is only available within the same app that the user started the drag.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Drag and drop is considered an important program construction approach in many end-user development systems.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] In contrast to more traditional, text-based programming languages, many end-user programming languages are based on visual components such as tiles or icons that are manipulated by end users through drag-and-drop interfaces.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Drag and drop is also featured in many shader editing programs for graphics tools, such as Blender.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] Drag and drop also features in some video game engines, including Unreal Engine, GameMaker Studio, Construct 2 and, with expansion, Unity.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-and-drop] A common example is dragging an icon on a virtual desktop to a special trashcan icon to delete a file.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Central to the Drag and Drop API are the various drag events that fire in a specific order and are expected to be handled in a specific way.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This document describes the steps that occur during a drag and drop operation, and what the application is supposed to do within each handler.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The drag starts on a draggable item, which can be a selection, a draggable element (including links, images, and any element with `draggable="true"`), a file from the operating system's file explorer, etc.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] First, the `dragstart` event is fired on the *source node*, which is the draggable element or, for selections, the text node that the drag started on.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If this event is cancelled, then the drag operation is aborted.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Otherwise, the `pointercancel` event is also fired on the source node.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The `dragstart` event is the only time you can modify the `dataTransfer`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For a custom draggable element, you almost always want to modify the drag data, which is covered in detail in Modifying the drag data store.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] There are two other things you can change: the feedback image and the allowed drop effects.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In this example, we add a listener for the `dragstart` event by using the `addEventListener()` method.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You could also listen to a higher ancestor as drag events bubble up as most other events do.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] When a drag occurs, a translucent image is generated from the source node, and follows the user's pointer during the drag.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This image is created automatically, so you do not need to create it yourself.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] However, you can use `setDragImage()` to specify a custom drag feedback image.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This reference will typically be to an `<img>` element, but it can also be to a `<canvas>` or any other element.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The feedback image will be generated from whatever the image looks like on screen, although for images, they will be drawn at their original size.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The second and third arguments to the `setDragImage()` method are offsets where the image should appear relative to the mouse pointer.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You can also use images and canvases that are not in a document.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In this example, we make one canvas the drag image.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] As the canvas is 50×50 pixels, we use offsets of half of this (`25`) so that the image appears centered on the mouse pointer.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For the entire course of the drag operation, all device input events (such as mouse or keyboard) are suppressed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The dragged data can be moved over various elements in the document, or even elements in other documents.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Whenever a new element is entered, a `dragenter` event is fired on that element, and a `dragleave` event is fired on the previous element.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Every few hundred milliseconds, two events fire: a `drag` event at the source node, and a `dragover` event at the element the drag is currently inside.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Most areas of a web page or application are not valid places to drop data, so elements by default ignore any drop that happened on it.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The element can elect itself to be a valid drop target by cancelling the `dragover` event.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If the element is an editable text field, such as a `<textarea>` or `<input type="text">`, and the data store contains one `text/plain` item, then the element is a valid drop target by default without cancelling `dragover`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You usually only want the drop target to accept drops in certain situations (for example, only if a link is being dragged).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] To do this, check a condition and only cancel the event when the condition is met.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In this example, we use the `includes` method to check if the type `text/uri-list` is present in the list of types.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If it is, we will cancel the event so that a drop may be allowed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If the drag data does not contain a link, the event will not be cancelled, and a drop cannot occur at that location.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Now the user is dragging into a valid drop target.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] There are several ways in which you can indicate to the user that a drop is allowed at this location, and what might happen if the drop happens.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Usually, the mouse pointer will update as necessary depending on the value of the `dropEffect` property.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Although the exact appearance depends on the user's platform, typically a plus sign icon will appear for a `copy` for example, and a "cannot drop here" icon will appear when a drop is not allowed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This mouse pointer feedback is sufficient in many cases.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The data will be simultaneously present at the source and target locations after dropping.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The data will only be present at the target location, and will be removed from the source location.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Some form of linking will be created between the source and drop locations; there is only one instance of the data at the source location.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] With the `dragenter` and `dragover` events, the `dropEffect` property is initialized to the effect that the user is requesting.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The user can modify the desired effect by pressing modifier keys.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Although the exact keys used vary by platform, typically the Shift and Control keys would be used to switch between copying, moving, and linking.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The mouse pointer will change to indicate which operation is desired.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For instance, for a `copy`, the cursor might appear with a plus sign next to it.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You can modify the `dropEffect` property during the `dragenter` or `dragover` events, if for example, a particular drop target only supports certain operations.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You can modify the `dropEffect` property to override the user effect, and enforce a specific drop operation to occur.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In this example, move is the effect that is performed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You can use the value `none` to indicate that no drop is allowed at this location.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You should usually do this if the element is only temporarily not accepting drops; if it's not intended to be a drop target, you should just not cancel the event.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Note that setting `dropEffect` only indicates the desired effect *at this particular instant*; a later `dragover` dispatch may change it.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] To persist the choice, you must set it in every `dragover` event.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Also, this effect is only *informational*, and what effects ends up being implemented depends on both the source and the target nodes (for example, if the source node cannot be modified, then even if a "move" effect is requested, it may not be possible).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For both user gestures and programmatically setting `dropEffect`, by default, all three drop effects are available.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The draggable element can restrict itself to only allow certain effects by setting the `effectAllowed` property within a `dragstart` event listener.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In this example, only a copy or link operation is allowed, but a move operation is not possible to be selected either via script or via user gestures.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] By default, the `dropEffect` is initialized based on `effectAllowed`, in the order of `copy`, `link`, `move`, selecting the first one that is allowed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The unselected but allowed effects may also be selected as default if appropriate; for example, on Windows, holding the Alt key causes `link` to be used in priority.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If `effectAllowed` is `uninitialized` and the dragged element is an `<a>` link, the default `dropEffect` is `link`; if `effectAllowed` is `uninitialized` and the dragged element is a selection from an editable text field, the default `dropEffect` is `move`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For more complex visual effects, you can perform other operations during the `dragenter` event, for example, by inserting an element at the location where the drop will occur.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This might be an insertion marker or an element that represents the dragged element in its new location.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] To do this, you could create an `<img>` element and insert it into the document during the `dragenter` event.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The `dragover` event will fire at the element the mouse is pointing at.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Naturally, you may need to move the insertion marker around inside the `dragover` event handler as well.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You can use the event's `clientX` and `clientY` properties as with other mouse events to determine the location of the mouse pointer.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Finally, the `dragleave` event will fire at an element when the drag leaves the element.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This is the time when you should remove any insertion markers or highlighting.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The `dragleave` event will always fire, even if the drag is cancelled, so you can always ensure that any insertion point cleanup can be done during this event.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For a practical example of using these events, see our Kanban board example.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] When the user releases the mouse, the drag and drop operation ends.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In order for the drop to be *potentially successful*, the drop must happen over a valid drop target, and the `dropEffect` must not be `none` at the time of mouse release.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Otherwise, the drop operation is considered failed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If the drop is potentially successful, a `drop` event is fired on the drop target.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You need to cancel this event using `preventDefault()` in order for the drop to be considered actually successful.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Otherwise, the drop is also considered successful if the drop was dropping text (the data contains a `text/plain` item) into an editable text field.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In this case, the text is inserted into the field (either at the cursor position or at the end, depending on platform conventions) and, if the `dropEffect` is `move` while the source is a selection within an editable region, the source is removed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Otherwise, for all other drag data and drop targets, the drop is considered failed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] During the `drop` event, you should retrieve the desired data from the drag data store using `DataTransfer.getData()`, and insert it at the drop location.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You can use the `dropEffect` property to determine which drag operation was desired.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The `drop` event is the only time when you can read the drag data store, other than `dragstart`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In the example here, once the data has been retrieved, we insert the string as the textual content of the target.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This has the effect of inserting the dragged text where it was dropped, assuming that the drop target is an area of text such as a `p` or `div` element.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The `getData()` method returns an empty string if the data store does not contain data of the specified type.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If you implemented conditional drop targets, this situation should not occur, because the drop target should only accept drops when the desired data is present.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You can retrieve other types of data as well.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If the data is a link, it should have the type `text/uri-list`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] You could then insert a link into the content.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For more information about how to read drag data, see Working with the drag data store.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] It is also the source and the target elements' responsibility to collaborate to implement the `dropEffect`—the source listens for the `dragend` event and the target listens for the `drop` event.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For example, if the `dropEffect` is `move`, then one of these elements must remove the dragged item from its old location (usually the source element itself, because the target element doesn't necessarily know or have control over the source).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] For cases 1 and 3, if the abortion happens while hovering over a valid drop target, the drop target receives a `dragleave` event, as if the drop no longer happens over it, so that it can clean up any drop feedback.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] In all cases, the `dropEffect` is set to `none` for subsequent events.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Afterwards, a `dragend` event is fired at the source node.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The browser may display an animation of the dragged selection going back to the source of the drag-and-drop operation.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Once the drag is complete, a `dragend` event is fired at the source of the drag (the same element that received the `dragstart` event).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] This event will fire regardless of whether the drag succeeded.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] If the `dropEffect` property has the value `none` during a `dragend`, then the drag was cancelled.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] Otherwise, the effect specifies which operation was performed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The source can use this information after a `move` operation to remove the dragged item from the old location.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] A drop can occur inside the same window or over another application.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The `dragend` event will always fire regardless.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] The event's `screenX` and `screenY` properties will be set to the screen coordinates where the drop occurred.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/drag-operations] After the `dragend` event has finished propagating, the drag and drop operation is complete.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/global-attributes-draggable] The **`draggable`** global attribute is an enumerated attribute that indicates whether the element can be dragged, either with native browser behavior or the HTML Drag and Drop API.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/global-attributes-draggable] The `draggable` attribute may be applied to elements that strictly fall under the HTML namespace, which means that it cannot be applied to SVGs.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/global-attributes-draggable] For more information about what namespace declarations look like, and what they do, see Namespace crash course.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/global-attributes-draggable] If this attribute is not set, its default value is `auto`, which means drag behavior is the default browser behavior: only text selections, images, and links can be dragged.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/global-attributes-draggable] For other elements, the event `ondragstart` must be set for drag and drop to work, as shown in this comprehensive example.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] The user may select *draggable* elements with a mouse, drag those elements to a *droppable* element, and drop them by releasing the mouse button.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] A translucent representation of the *draggable* elements follows the pointer during the drag operation.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] You can customize which elements can become *draggable*, the type of feedback the *draggable* elements produce, and the *droppable* elements.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] This overview of HTML Drag and Drop includes a description of the interfaces, basic steps to add drag-and-drop support to an application, and an interoperability summary of the interfaces.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] On the surface, Drag and Drop actually has three distinct use cases: dragging elements within a page, dragging data out of a page, and dragging data into a page.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] They have subtly different requirements and implementations.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] However, the Drag and Drop API provides a unified model to think about all these interactions.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] We'll look at how each one can be defined and used.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] HTML drag-and-drop uses the DOM event model and *drag events* inherited from mouse events.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] During drag operations, several event types are fired, and some events might fire many times, such as the `drag` and `dragover` events.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Similarly, the `dragenter`, `dragleave`, `dragover`, and `drop` events are fired on elements that are potential drop targets, and therefore can't fire when dragging an item out of the browser.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For more information, see Drag operations.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] In HTML, images, links, and selections are draggable by default.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] To make an arbitrary element draggable, set the `draggable` attribute to the value `"true"`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For images and links, `draggable` defaults to `true`, so you would only set it to `false` to disable dragging of these elements.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For non-draggable elements, the "dragging" gesture usually selects the text instead.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] In this case, the *source node*, or the node on which various events such as `dragstart` and `dragend` are fired, is the text node that the drag started on.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] The selection can partially or fully contain multiple nodes, including text nodes and element nodes, which are all considered dragged simultaneously.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] As aforementioned, the dragged item can also be something not on a webpage—for example, a file in the operating system's file explorer.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] However, only items on the webpage can cause the `dragstart` and `dragend` events to fire.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For more information, see the Drag operations guide.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] You can't transfer JavaScript objects directly to arbitrary webpages, and surely not to external applications, so to transfer data in and out of the webpage, the data must be serialized to a string (or as a `File`).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] In drag and drop, this string is encapsulated in a `DataTransferItem` object, which also defines a particular `type`—typically a MIME type such as `text/html`—that defines how the string should be interpreted.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Each drag and drop operation has an associated *drag data store*, which is a `DataTransfer` object accessible via the `DragEvent`'s `dataTransfer` property.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For the default-draggable items such as images, links, and selections, the drag data is already defined by the browser; for custom draggable elements defined using the `draggable` attribute, you must define the drag data yourself.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] The only time to make any modifications to the data store is within the `dragstart` handler—for the `dataTransfer` of any other drag event, the data store is unmodifiable.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] The `setData()` method can be used to add an item to the drag data, as shown in the following example.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Furthermore, the only time you can *read* from the data store, apart from the `dragstart` event, is during the `drop` event (allowing the drop target to retrieve the data).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For all other events, the data store cannot be accessed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For more information, read Working with the drag data store.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] A *drop target* is an element on which a user can drop a dragged item.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] By default, most elements are not drop targets, and if you release the drag, a "fly-back" animation displays, indicating that the drag and drop failed.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Any element can become a drop target by canceling the `dragover` event that fires on it with `preventDefault()`.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] The `drop` event only fires on drop targets, and it is the only time you can read the drag data store.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] The following example shows a minimal valid drop target, and also combines the code from the previous examples.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] For more information, see Specifying drop targets.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Describes the steps that occur during a drag and drop operation, and what the application is supposed to do within each handler.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Describes how to read and write to the drag data store during a drag and drop operation.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] A hands-on guide implementing a basic interface accepting file drops.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] A hands-on guide implementing a Kanban board involving dragging and dropping elements within a webpage.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] The event object passed to drag event handlers.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Holds any data transferred between contexts, consisting of text items and file items.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Initially designed for drag and drop, it is now also used in other contexts such as Clipboard API.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Represents one item in the drag data store, which can be a text item or a file item.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Represents the list of `DataTransferItem` objects in the drag data store.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/html-drag-and-drop-api] Reference pages for each interface also have individual examples.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] In computing, a **pointing device gesture** or **mouse gesture** (or simply **gesture**) is a way of combining pointing device or finger movements and clicks that the software recognizes as a specific computer event and responds to accordingly.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] They can be useful for people who have difficulties typing on a keyboard.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] For example, in a web browser, a user can navigate to the previously viewed page by pressing the right pointing device button, moving the pointing device briefly to the left, then releasing the button.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] The first pointing device gesture, the "drag", was introduced by Apple to replace a dedicated "move" button on mice shipped with its Macintosh and Lisa computers.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Dragging involves holding down a pointing device button while moving the pointing device; the software interprets this as an action distinct from separate clicking and moving behaviors.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Unlike most pointing device gestures, it does not involve the tracing of any particular shape.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Although the "drag" behavior has been adopted in a huge variety of software packages, few other gestures have been as successful.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] As of 2005, most programs do not support gestures other than the drag operation.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Each program that recognizes pointing device gestures does so in its own way, sometimes allowing for very short mouse movement distances to be recognized as gestures, and sometimes requiring very precise emulation of a certain movement pattern (e.g. circle).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Some implementations allow users to customize these factors.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] For example, in the *Myth* real-time tactics series, originally created by Bungie, players use them to order battlefield units to face in a desired direction.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Another game using gestures is Lionhead's *Black & White*.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] The game *Arx Fatalis* uses mouse gestures for drawing runes in the air to cast spells.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Several Nintendo Wii games take advantage of such a system.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] *Ōkami* uses a system similar to mouse gestures; the player can enter a drawing mode in which the shape they create (circle, lightning bolt, line, etc.) performs a function in the game such as creating a bomb or changing the time from night to day.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Other examples of computer games that use mouse gestures are *Die by the Sword* and *Silver* where basic mouse gestures actually map attack moves and such in real-time combat, along with *MX vs.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] ATV: Reflex*, which has a control scheme that implements its titular rider "reflex" system with mouse gestures.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] The Nintendo Switch 2's Joy-Con 2 controllers, which also double as mice, can also support mouse gestures, as evidenced in the online sports game *Drag x Drive*.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] The Opera web browser has recognized gestures since version 5.10 (April 2001) but this feature was disabled by default.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] However, this feature was introduced in Vivaldi Browser, a web browser meant to be a solution for the users of the former Opera, a more powerful browser than the current one.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Opera browser also supports mouse chording which serves a similar function but doesn't necessitate mouse movement.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] The first browser that used advanced mouse gestures (in 2002) was Maxthon, in which a highly customizable interface allowed the assignment of almost every action to one of 52 mouse gestures and few mouse chords.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Several mouse gesture extensions are also available for the Mozilla Firefox browser.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] These extensions use almost identical gestures as Opera.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Some tools provide mouse gestures support in any application for Microsoft Windows.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] K Desktop Environment 3 includes universal mouse gesture support since version 3.2.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Windows Aero provides three mouse gestures called Aero Peek, Aero Shake and Aero Snap.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] See the corresponding article for a description.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Touchscreens of tablet-type devices, such as the iPad, utilize multi-touch technology, with gestures acting as the main form of user interface.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Many touchpads, which in laptops replace the traditional mouse, have similar gesture support.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] For example, a common gesture is to use two fingers in a downwards or upwards motion to scroll the currently active page.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] The rising popularity of touchscreen interfaces has led to gestures becoming a more standard feature in computing.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Windows 7 introduced touchscreen support and touchpad gestures.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Its successor, Windows 8 is designed to run both on traditional desktops and mobile devices and hence gestures are now enabled by default where the hardware allows it.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Related to gestures are touchpad hotspots, where a particular region of the touchpad has additional functionality.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] For example, a common hotspot feature is the far right side of the touchpad, which will scroll the active page if a finger is dragged down or up it.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Multi-touch touchscreen gestures are predefined motions used to interact with multi-touch devices.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] An increasing number of products like smartphones, tablets, laptops or desktop computers have functions that are triggered by multi-touch gestures.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Other gestures including more than 2 fingers on screen have also been developed such as Sticky Tools.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] These techniques are often developed for 3D applications and are not considered standard.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] A major drawback of current gesture interaction solutions is the lack of support for two necessary user interface design principles, feedback and visibility (or affordance).
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Feedback notification is required to indicate whether the gesture has been entered correctly by indicating the gesture recognized and the corresponding command activated, although Sensiva does approach this to some extent in providing voice notification.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] The other principle is visibility of gestures, providing the user some means of learning the necessary gestures and the contexts they can be used in.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Both Mouse Gestures for Internet Explorer and ALToolbar Mouse Gestures display colored tracers that indicate the current motion that the user is taking to facilitate visual clues for the user.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Pie menus and marking menus have been proposed as solutions for both problems, since they support learning of the available options but can also be used with quick gestures.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Most recent versions of Opera (11 and above) uses an on-screen pie menu to simply and instructively display which mouse gestures are available and how to activate them, providing feedback and visibility.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] One limitation with gesture interaction is the scope context in which the gestures can be used.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] For example, each gesture has only one corresponding command for each application window.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] Holding down buttons while moving the mouse can be awkward and requires some practice, since the downwards action increases friction for the horizontal motion.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] An optical mouse would be less susceptible to changes in behavior than a ball mouse with increased friction because the sensor does not rely on mechanical contact to sense movement; a touchpad provides no added friction with all its buttons held down with a thumb.
[src:drag-and-drop-api/pointing-device-gesture] However, it was also argued that muscular tension resulting from holding down buttons could be exploited in user interface design as it gives constant feedback that the user is in a temporary state, or mode (Buxton, 1995).
